
[1]oyer

   OY'ER, n.

   1. In law, a hearing or trial of causes. A court of oyer and terminer
   is constituted by a commission to inquire, hear and determine all
   treasons, felonies and misdemeanors.

   2. The hearing, as of a writ, bond, note or other specialty; as when a
   defendant in court prays oyer of a writing.
